  "plan": "1) Search the filesystem for any MySQL socket files (this will reveal if a server is running under a different socket path). 2) Search /app and /etc for common DB config or environment files that might contain DB connection info (look for strings like mysql, mariadb, DB_HOST, DB_USER, DB_PASS, DATABASE_URL). 3) Inspect /etc/mysql for configs. 4) Check service status for mysql and attempt to start the service if no external DB info is found. If we find connection info we will use it to run SQL queries; otherwise, if we successfully start a local server we'll run SHOW DATABASES to confirm. I will run these checks and then either request DB credentials or proceed to operate against the discovered server.",
